= Implementation

This section should describe all components of your software implementation, emphasising particularly novel or nuanced components of code or its structure. There is no need to document every line of code, but you may include snippets as appropriate. You may wish to include code snippets and screenshots as figures to provide detail where necessary. At MSc level, an artefact with very high technical complexity is expected, and the implementation should be very well documented.

== System Architecture and Technical Overview

Provide a high-level overview of the system architecture. This may include architecture diagrams, descriptions of major components and their interactions, and the technologies used. This gives the reader the big picture before diving into specifics.

== Core Design and Mechanics

Describe the core design decisions behind your artefact. For software projects, this might cover key design patterns or architectural decisions. For games projects, this could include the core concept, gameplay loops, level design, key mechanics, and design goals.

== Implementation Details

Document the most significant or technically interesting aspects of your implementation. This might be broken into subsections covering different subsystems or modules. Focus on what is novel, complex, or noteworthy — avoid documenting trivial or boilerplate code.

== Testing and Quality Assurance

Describe the testing conducted during development (e.g., unit tests, integration tests, playtesting). Document any bugs found and how they were resolved.

== Deployment and Performance

If applicable, describe how the software was deployed and any performance considerations or optimisations made.

== Source Code and Documentation

Describe how the source code is organised and where it can be found. Note any documentation provided (e.g., README files, API documentation, user guides).
